This Ode has been very generally referred to the voyage of virgil to Athens, from which he returned only to die in B.C. 19. This, however, would fix its composition four years later than the (late which the con- siderations suggested by Od. 1. 12 lead us to assign to the publication of Books i iii; nor is it an Ode which seems very likely to have been inserted after publication. Given to the world in Virgil' 5 1116111116, it seems playful and affectionate, but it would seem cold and irrelevant to be published aster his early death, and in a volurne in which it was the sole record of their friends-bip. Frauke felt the difficulty so much that he proposed to read ‘Quintilium' sor ‘ Virgilium‚‘ thinking that he could trace a correspondence between this Ode and 1. 24, especially in 1·. 11 ‘ heu non ita cre(litum.’ It has even been suggested that it may have been another Virgilius, as is the case probably with Od. 4. 1². The simplest solution would be that the reference is to another voyage. All we know even of the voyage in 13.6. 19 is due to the fragmentary biography which goes by the name of Donatus, and which is not sup- posed to be earlier than the fifth century.
